import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score

# read dataset
data = pd.read_csv("salary_multi.csv", header=None)

# convert horizontal dataset to vertical format
data = data.set_index(0).T
data.columns = ["Age","Experience","Income"]

data = data.astype(float)

X = data[["Age","Experience"]]
y = data["Income"]

# model
model = LinearRegression()
model.fit(X,y)

# prediction
y_pred = model.predict(X)

# evaluation
sse = np.sum((y - y_pred)**2)
msse = sse / len(y)
mae = mean_absolute_error(y,y_pred)
rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y,y_pred))
rmsle = np.sqrt(np.mean((np.log1p(y_pred)-np.log1p(y))**2))
r2 = r2_score(y,y_pred)

print("SSE:",sse)
print("MSSE:",msse)
print("MAE:",mae)
print("RMSE:",rmse)
print("RMSLE:",rmsle)
print("R2 Score:",r2)


Problem Understanding & Aim
To predict employee income based on age and experience using Multiple Linear Regression.

Data Collection & Pre-Processing
Dataset contains Age, Experience and Income.
Data is loaded using pandas and separated into X and y variables.

Model Design / Algorithm Selection
Multiple Linear Regression is used because there are two independent variables.

Implementation – Model Building
Import libraries.
Load dataset.
Train regression model.
Predict income values.

Evaluation & Output
Model performance measured using SSE, MSSE, MAE, RMSE, RMSLE and R² score.

Viva / Concept Clarity
Multiple Linear Regression predicts a dependent variable using two or more independent variables.
